Network troubleshooting.

When the network is not working, the fastest way to find the fault is to work through the layers in order, from your own machine outward, ruling out one possibility at a time. Start at the very bottom: am I even connected? Check the interfaces with the brief form of i-p link to see whether any are down, and i-p address to confirm you actually hold an address. If an interface is down or has no address, fix that first, whether it is a d-h-c-p failure, an unplugged cable, or a configuration issue.

Next, can I reach my gateway? Ask which gateway will be used with i-p route get, and then ping it. Ping sends small echo requests and waits for replies; if every packet is lost or the host is unreachable, the problem is local, on your own network segment. If the gateway answers, move outward: can I reach the wider internet? Ping a stable, well-known public address. If the gateway pings but external addresses do not, something between you and the outside, the gateway, a firewall, or your provider, is blocking traffic.

Then test dee-en-ess, which is a surprisingly common culprit. Use dig to look a name up, and crucially dig again against a public server to bypass your own resolver. If the public-server query works but your normal lookup does not, your resolver is broken rather than the network. If you need to see where along the path a connection dies, trace-route shows every hop a packet takes to the destination along with the latency to each, and the hop that suddenly starts timing out points at the trouble spot; the m-t-r tool combines trace-route and ping into one live screen, which is invaluable for intermittent faults. And finally, to check whether a specific remote service is actually listening, you can test the port directly with a tool like net-cat. Working the layers in this order, connection, address, gateway, internet, dee-en-ess, path, and port, turns a vague it-is-not-working into a precise diagnosis very quickly.
